observations.recommendation:
Thru the Inventory Committee, conduct physical inventory of all items of PPE of the Municipality and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment, within the prescribed period in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, for the timely review and verification of the PPE accounts;

Thru the Inventory Committee, prepare the inventory report in accordance with the prescribed format in order to provide valuable information necessary in the reconciliation of balances;

Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile with accounting records to make the records reflective of the actual count of PPEs;

Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and

Direct the GSO to maintain Property Cards for each item of the PPE pursuant to Section 114, Paragraph 4 of the MNGAs for LGUs, Volume I.

Require the Inventory Committee to submit the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Networks to the Office of the Auditor, using the prescribed format, within the prescribed period for timely verification and the reconciliation of the list of inventory per Local Road Inventory Report and Road Map with those recorded in the Road Networks account;

Instruct the GSO to maintain Local Road Network Property Card to indicate the status and condition of each road network and its components;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to properly disclose the details of the total road network system in the Notes to Financial Statements in the format prescribed by COA Circular No. 2015-008; and

Enjoin the concerned officials and employees to strictly comply with COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015 to ensure fair presentation of the Local Road Network account in the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Management undertake the following:
Thru the Inventory Committee, conduct a complete inventory count of all PPEs of the LGU and prepare and submit a Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment within the prescribed period, providing complete information necessary in the reconciliation of balances;
Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile the same with accounting records to make the records reflective of the actual count of PPEs;
Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements;
Direct the GSO to maintain Property Cards for each item of the PPE pursuant to Section 114, Paragraph 4 of the MNGAs for LGUs, Volume I;
The General Services Officer to conduct inspection of all the unserviceable properties of the LGU and prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report for Unserviceable Property, after which, proceed with the disposal procedures in accordance with Section 379 of the Local Government Code and the Revised Manual on the Disposal of Government Properties; and
After the disposal, completely provide the necessary details on the Inspection and Disposal portion of the IIRUP, which shall be the basis for the derecognition in the books of account.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the Inventory Committee to submit the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Networks to the Office of the Auditor, using the prescribed format, within the prescribed period for timely verification and the reconciliation of the list of inventory per Local Road Inventory Report and Road Map with those recorded in the Road Networks account;
Instruct the GSO to maintain Local Road Network Property Card to indicate the status and condition of each road networks and its components;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to properly disclose the details of the total road network system in the Notes to Financial Statements in the format prescribed by the said Circular;
Direct the Inventory Committee to properly prepare the RPCLRN and to coordinate with the Municipal Assessor to provide costing of the land where the local road networks are situated/erected, and with the Municipal Engineer to provide the length and the cost of each road network component; and
Enjoin the concerned officials and employees to strictly comply to COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015 to ensure fair presentation of the Local Road Network account in the Financial Statements.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Ensure the timely reclassification of completed projects from the Construction in Progress account to the appropriate Property, Plant, and Equipment accounts immediately upon project completion, as required under Section 50, Chapter 3 of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System for Local Government Units, Volume I;
Recognize depreciation expenses in the period the assets become available for use, in accordance with Paragraph 71 of IPSAS 17, to reflect accurate balances in the Statement of Financial Position and Statement of Financial Performance;
Record the transfer of the completed infrastructure projects in CY 2018 amounting to P5,193,032.20 from CIP to appropriate PPE account and recognize the total depreciation expense and the corresponding accumulated depreciation; and
Compute the depreciation expense of the PPE accounts pertaining to infrastructure projects completed in CY 2024 from the period the PPE accounts were available for use until the end of the year, thereby ensuring the reliability of the reported surplus.

We recommended that the Management:
Continue the implementation of the projects funded under the 20% Development Fund and show their commitment in serving the constituents of the Municipality;
Coordinate with the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and Municipal Engineer to carefully plan and schedule each project’s implementation and to ensure timely implementation and completion of development projects;
Revert all savings from completed projects to the unappropriated surplus, which shall be available for use for other expenditures or priority development projects of the LGU; and
Review the unimplemented project amounting to P50,000.00 and consider whether to reprogram this fund to other priority development projects to address the current needs of the constituents.

Require the concerned barangays to submit immediately the liquidation reports for fund transfers totaling P4.806 million;
Assign a person responsible/in-charge in monitoring the submission of liquidation reports due for submission and issue demand letters to concerned barangays who failed to comply. This will ensure immediate submission of liquidation reports after the purpose/s for which it was granted has been served or completed;
Cease the payment of fund transfer unless the required certification that previous fund transfers have already been liquidated or accounted for, thus avoiding accumulation of past due accounts pursuant to Item 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012; and
Initiate the request for write-off of the unaccounted balance amounting to P0.127 million of the Due from LGUs account in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

Require the Human Resource Management Officer to submit a copy of the monthly approved Daily Time Record or a certification of actual number of workdays performed as basis in the computation of the allowable amount due to each claimant pursuant to Item 7 of Local Budget Circular No. 103;

Direct the Municipal Accountant not to process payrolls for RATA without the above required documents; and

Stop the granting of transportation allowance to municipal officials and employees who are actually using government vehicles in the performance of their official functions.

